        {
          "id": "5dabb155-a046-4478-b3fb-2d8184dd2ec7",
          "estimatedTime": 5,
          "title": "Step 3: Write Rubric Criteria",
          "description": "",
          "courseSectionItems": [
            {
              "id": "3331ac13-dcbf-42f3-b002-35178942b6b0",
              "weight": 0,
              "type": "rich_text",
              "contents": {
                "singleSelect": true,
                "body": "<img src=\"https://static.remotasks.com/uploads/6892e922522126f1742d8678/1754469826705_qvc8d.png\" alt=\"Step 3: Write Rubric Criteria\">"
              },
              "_id": "689704a61db81d7051a20000"
            },
            {
              "id": "d959f78b-0a93-4bde-985a-3daa7731e151",
              "weight": 0,
              "type": "rich_text",
              "contents": {
                "singleSelect": true,
                "body": "<img src=\"https://static.remotasks.com/uploads/6892e922522126f1742d8678/1754513611345_7hcc3.png\" alt=\"You’ll now write a full rubric that captures what makes a good final response.  Cover all key asks from the prompt—nothing critical should be missing.  Include clear, specific criteria with appropriate weights.  Tag each criterion with:  A category (e.g., Visual Perception, Truthfulness)  Whether it’s explicit or implicit  Whether it’s objective or subjective  Section: Use Clear and Positive Wording  Strong rubric criteria are specific, concise, and easy to apply.  Use positive phrasing that includes relevant object details rather than doesn’t leave anything out.  Avoid vague language like “good description” or “somewhat accurate.”  Remove any redundancy—each criterion should evaluate a distinct concept.  Avoid using technical scoring terms like “fraction” unless defined clearly.  Image Description:  The image on the right side of the slide is a screenshot from a rubric creation interface. It shows a form where a user writes a rubric criterion and assigns it a point value, category, and labels for explicit/implicit and objective/subjective. Example criteria are listed at the bottom, such as:  “The response provides exactly two exit numbers.” (3 points – Visual Perception – Implicit – Objective)  “The response only identifies the exit numbers that appear in the left half of the billboard as 6 and 2.” (1 point – Truthfulness – Implicit – Objective)\">"
              },
              "_id": "689704a61db81d7051a20001"
            },
            {
              "id": "3240b38c-0b16-4d0a-87ee-0e896a46da08",
              "weight": 0,
              "type": "rich_text",
              "contents": {
                "singleSelect": true,
                "body": "<img src=\"https://static.remotasks.com/uploads/6892e922522126f1742d8678/1754469861887_54i1s.png\" alt=\"What Makes a Criterion Strong?  Clear, Specific, and Actionable expectations → Each criterion should describe exactly what the model is expected to do. → Use testable phrases like: &quot;The response includes at least two reasons.&quot; → Avoid vague terms like “appropriate” or “good” unless they are clearly defined.  Checkable and Self-Contained → Criteria should be easy to check against the response without relying on other items or extra interpretation. → Don’t require the rater to infer or imagine beyond what’s presented. → Each criterion should stand on its own — it shouldn’t depend on understanding another rubric item to make sense.  Aligned with the Prompt → Ground expectations in the task instructions and goals of the prompt. → Rubrics should never expect something the prompt doesn’t support.\">"
              },
              "_id": "689704a61db81d7051a20002"
            },
            {
              "id": "5d6116ae-19ae-4403-ad6c-efceb22bcb4e",
              "weight": 0,
              "type": "rich_text",
              "contents": {
                "singleSelect": true,
                "body": "<img src=\"https://static.remotasks.com/uploads/6892e922522126f1742d8678/1754513823481_h1nl3w.png\" alt=\"Objective vs Subjective Criteria Rubrics should reflect everything the model is expected to do.  Objective Criteria Considered the foundation  Can be clearly identified as fulfilled or unfulfilled within a response  Factual and clearly verifiable  Aim for at least 75% objective criteria  Example: &quot;The response uses 5 bullet points&quot;  Subjective Criteria Require interpretation or personal judgment to determine fulfillment  Should be used sparingly  Example: &quot;The response has a polite tone&quot;  Avoid fully subjective criteria that leave too much room for disagreement and inconsistent scoring  Sometimes some prompt types require subjective criteria like &quot;Chatbot&quot;\">"
              },
              "_id": "689704a61db81d7051a20003"
