              "weight": 0,
              "type": "rich_text",
              "contents": {
                "singleSelect": true,
                "body": "<img src=\"https://static.remotasks.com/uploads/6892e922522126f1742d8678/1754548634293_pn4cq.png\" alt=\"Slide Title: Writing Hallucination Criteria  Section: When to Include Hallucination Criteria  Include hallucination criteria if the model introduces information that does not appear in the image or prompt.  This includes unrelated facts or fabricated details. Do not include hallucination criteria unless hallucinations are actually present in the response.  Unnecessary hallucination items are discouraged and can reduce rubric clarity.  If a hallucination is present, write a criterion that clearly identifies and penalizes the added or unrelated information.  Section: Why It Matters  Omitting required hallucination coverage means the model won’t be penalized appropriately.  This is considered a task fail and must be fixed before submitting.  Notes Section:  ➤ Some prompts only allow for one valid answer (e.g., logic, math).  ➤ Don’t use hallucination criteria just because only one answer is correct.  ➤ Use accuracy-based criteria instead (e.g., “The final answer must be X.”)  ➤ Hallucination criteria are unnecessary when correctness is already the focus.\">"
