              "type": "rich_text",
              "contents": {
                "singleSelect": true,
                "body": "<img src=\"https://static.remotasks.com/uploads/6892e922522126f1742d8678/1754544291768_k051we.png\" alt=\"Slide title reads “Literal vs. Common Language.” Subheading says: “If a word can be interpreted literally, auditors will often take the literal meaning — especially in STEM/Code tasks.”  Two side-by-side examples follow:  Example 1 (left box, light blue): Word: “girls” Prompt: Can you name the girls performing on stage? Expectation: The band name will be enough. Reality: Auditor takes “girls” literally and expects each girl to be named → ❌ Task fails.  Example 2 (right box, light purple): Word: “fraction” Prompt: What fraction of people... Expectation: Includes any reasonable format (%, decimals, etc.) Reality: Auditor only accepts x/y format → ❌ Criteria invalid → Task fails.  At the bottom of the slide is a light green box labeled Ideal Mindset, with a thought bubble icon. Text reads: “Could this word be misunderstood if taken literally?”\">"
